select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 60 ปี diagnosed with HCC 6 months ago — Child-Pugh B + advanced HCC + portal vein invasion + ascites + recently completed atezolizumab/bevacizumab but progression + ECOG 2 + พ่อแม่และบุตรหลายคน + ครอบครัวยอมรับยาก

คำถาม: integrative palliative + end-of-life care', '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue all aggressive treatment"},{"label":"B","text":"**Advanced HCC progression with limited treatment options — integrative palliative + serious illness conversations**: (1) **Multidisciplinary team meeting**: medical oncology, hepatology, palliative care, social work, chaplain, family medicine; (2) **Goals of care discussion** with patient + family — serious illness conversation framework (Ariadne Labs / Atul Gawande): - Understanding of illness + prognosis - What''s important to patient (values, fears, hopes) - What outcomes they want to avoid - What functional trade-offs acceptable - Family wishes + dynamics - Cultural + spiritual considerations; (3) **Prognostic estimation**: - Advanced HCC + Child B + progression on first-line + ECOG 2 → median survival 3-6 months - Be honest but compassionate — ''hope for the best, prepare for the worst'' - Surprise question: ''would I be surprised if patient died in 12 months?'' — useful prognostic question; (4) **Treatment options to consider** (decreasing intensity): - Second-line systemic therapy (lenvatinib, sorafenib, regorafenib, cabozantinib, ramucirumab if AFP > 400) — limited efficacy; weigh toxicity vs benefit; ECOG 2 borderline candidacy - Locoregional therapy (TACE, Y90, SBRT) — for liver-predominant; limited utility in advanced - **Best supportive care + palliative care** — focus on QOL + symptom management; (5) **Concurrent palliative care from diagnosis of advanced disease** (per Temel JCO 2010 NEJM 2010 — improves QOL + may extend survival); not ''palliative or curative'' — both can coexist; (6) **Symptom management**: - **Pain**: WHO ladder; opioids — careful dose-adjust in hepatic impairment (avoid morphine accumulation in renal/hepatic, use hydromorphone or fentanyl; morphine OK at adjusted dose with monitoring); coadjuvants for neuropathic - **Ascites**: large-volume paracentesis as needed; sodium restriction + diuretic adjusted for hepatic dysfunction; PleurX catheter consideration for recurrent symptomatic - **Hepatic encephalopathy**: lactulose, rifaximin; treat precipitants - **Pruritus**: anti-histamine, cholestyramine, sertraline, naltrexone (caution) - **Nausea**: ondansetron, haloperidol, metoclopramide - **Fatigue**: address reversible (anemia, depression); pacing - **Anorexia / cachexia**: nutritional counseling; appetite stimulants limited efficacy (megestrol, mirtazapine, low-dose steroid); enteral if quality of life maintained - **Anxiety + depression**: SSRIs (sertraline, escitalopram), counseling - **Dyspnea**: oxygen, opioid (low-dose); (7) **Advance care planning + advance directive**: - Healthcare proxy designation - Living will - DNR / POLST discussion - Specific care preferences (intubation, dialysis, artificial nutrition); (8) **Hospice eligibility + referral**: - Medicare benefit if life expectancy ≤ 6 months + focus on comfort - Hospice services: comprehensive symptom management, nursing, social work, chaplain, volunteer, bereavement support, equipment, medications - Settings: home with hospice (preferred when feasible), inpatient hospice unit, residential, hospital; (9) **Family support**: - Anticipatory grief + counseling - Caregiver burden + respite - Family meeting facilitator (palliative care, social work) - Children''s understanding (age-appropriate communication; child life specialists if hospital-based) - Cultural + spiritual rituals respected - Practical support (legal, financial, social services); (10) **Spiritual care**: chaplain consultation; cultural + religious practices integrated; (11) **Bereavement**: continue support for family for 12+ months after death; identify complicated grief; (12) **Care team self-care**: addressing ''second patient'' issues — clinician grief, burnout prevention"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications immediately + send home"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse to discuss prognosis"},{"label":"E","text":"Continue all curative treatments aggressively"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Advanced cancer integrative palliative care** — concurrent palliative care from diagnosis of advanced disease improves outcomes (Temel NEJM 2010 — early integrated palliative care in NSCLC improved QOL + mood + survival). **Serious illness conversation framework** (Ariadne Labs, Gawande): 1. Set up the conversation (permission, dedicated time) 2. Assess understanding + information preferences 3. Share prognosis (sensitive but honest) 4. Explore key topics: - What''s important to you? - What are your fears + worries? - What goals do you have? - What outcomes are unacceptable? - How much are you willing to go through for the chance of more time? 5. Close the conversation (recommendation, plan) **Prognostication tools**: - Surprise question: ''would I be surprised if this patient died in 12 months?'' - Performance status (ECOG, Karnofsky) - Disease-specific prognostic models - Palliative Performance Scale (PPS) - PaP (Palliative Prognostic) Score **Symptom management in end-stage liver disease + cancer**: - Pain (opioid dose adjustment): avoid morphine accumulation in renal/hepatic dysfunction; hydromorphone (renal/hepatic safer), fentanyl (hepatic OK, transdermal stable in cachectic), methadone (caution, prolonged QT, complex pharmacology) - Ascites: paracentesis, diuretic (judicious), albumin replacement, PleurX catheter for recurrent - Hepatic encephalopathy: lactulose, rifaximin; treat precipitants (infection, GI bleed, dehydration, medications, constipation) - Pruritus: cholestyramine, sertraline, naltrexone, antihistamine - Anorexia / cachexia: nutritional support if QOL maintained; megestrol, mirtazapine, low-dose steroid (limited benefit); cannabinoids variable - Fatigue: address reversible (anemia, depression, hypothyroid, hypogonadism); methylphenidate selective benefit - Dyspnea: opioid (low-dose morphine 2.5 mg PO q4h or equivalent — central effect on dyspnea perception), oxygen, fan, positioning, anxiolytic **Advance care planning**: - Healthcare proxy designation - Living will - POLST / MOLST (Physician Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment) — actionable medical orders portable across settings - Code status discussion **Hospice eligibility (Medicare US)**: life expectancy ≤ 6 months + comfort-focused care + foregoing curative intent — hospice provides comprehensive interdisciplinary services (nursing, social work, chaplain, home health aide, bereavement, equipment, medications). **Family / caregiver support**: anticipatory grief, complicated grief screening, caregiver burden assessment, respite, social work, financial counseling, children''s services (Child Life), bereavement support 12+ months. **Cultural + spiritual sensitivity**: language, religious practices, family hierarchy, decision-making customs, end-of-life rituals — integrate into care plan. **Clinician wellbeing**: burnout prevention, debriefing, peer support, mental health resources — recognized critical for sustainable palliative + serious illness care delivery.', NULL,
  'hard', 'hemato_onco', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'hemato_onco', 'elderly',
  'ASCO Palliative Care Integration; Temel JS et al. NEJM 2010; Ariadne Labs Serious Illness Care; AAHPM', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_integrative'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 60 ปี diagnosed with HCC 6 months ago — Child-Pugh B + advanced HCC + portal vein invasion + ascites + recently completed atezolizumab/bevacizumab but progression + ECOG 2 + พ่อแม่และบุตรหลายคน + ครอบครัวยอมรับยาก

คำถาม: integrative palliative + end-of-life care'
