select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'หญิงไทยอายุ 25 ปี severe anxiety + abdominal pain RLQ + nausea but normal vitals + normal labs; previously suspected appendicitis but US negative + clinical improved overnight; planning discharge

คำถาม: management of equivocal abdominal pain', '[{"label":"A","text":"Force surgery"},{"label":"B","text":"**Equivocal abdominal pain — observation + serial reassessment + targeted workup**: (1) **Serial abdominal exam** by same examiner — most valuable diagnostic tool; (2) **Active observation** in ED / observation unit 4-12h — many self-resolve OR develop clear features; (3) **Repeat labs** at 6-12h if not improving — WBC trend, CRP; (4) **Imaging** as guided: - US first (radiation-free, pelvic + abdominal) - CT if clinical worsening or persistent unclear - MRI if pregnant; (5) **Other differentials to consider** in young woman with RLQ pain: - GI: appendicitis (early or atypical), Meckel''s, mesenteric adenitis, Crohn''s terminal ileitis, infectious enteritis - GYN: ovarian cyst (rupture, torsion — surgical emergency), ectopic pregnancy (check β-hCG always), PID, endometriosis, mittelschmerz - GU: UTI, ureteral colic - Musculoskeletal: psoas, hip - Other: functional, anxiety-related; (6) **β-hCG mandatory** in reproductive-age female with abdominal pain; (7) **Discharge criteria**: - Clinical improvement - Pain controlled - Tolerating PO - Reliable patient + access to follow-up - Clear return precautions (worsening pain, fever, vomiting, inability to eat, peritonitis signs); (8) **Education** + follow-up clinic 24-48h; (9) **Document carefully** — return reasons, time of resolution, expected course"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge without follow-up"},{"label":"D","text":"Long-term opioid prescription"},{"label":"E","text":"Surgery indicated regardless"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Equivocal acute abdomen** — common scenario; balance between unnecessary surgery (negative laparotomy/laparoscopy ~ 10-15%) and missed serious diagnosis. **Diagnostic approach**: 1. Serial exam by same provider — most valuable 2. Active observation (4-12 hr) 3. Repeat labs (WBC trend) 4. Imaging escalation (US → CT) 5. β-hCG always in reproductive-age female 6. Consider gynecologic differentials in females Use ''safety netting'' — clear return precautions, follow-up. Use ''shared decision-making'' regarding observation vs intervention. Documentation important. **Pain management during observation**: appropriate analgesia does not mask diagnosis (clinical exam preserved with opioid administration per modern evidence — old dogma debunked). Multimodal analgesia preferred.', NULL,
  'easy', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'gi', 'adult',
  'Surgical Decision Making — ACS; AAST Guidelines', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
