select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: surgical anatomy — abdominal wall + hernias

คำถาม: abdominal wall anatomy + hernia classification', '[{"label":"A","text":"Anatomy not relevant"},{"label":"B","text":"**Abdominal wall anatomy + hernia types**: (1) **Layers** (outside to inside): skin, subcutaneous (Camper''s fascia + Scarpa''s fascia), external oblique aponeurosis, internal oblique, transversus abdominis, transversalis fascia, peritoneum; (2) **Rectus abdominis sheath**: above arcuate line — anterior (EO + ½ IO) + posterior (½ IO + TA); below arcuate line — all anterior (rectus directly on transversalis fascia + peritoneum) — explains lower abdominal hernias predilection; (3) **Linea alba** midline fibrous raphe; **linea semilunaris** lateral border of rectus; **arcuate line (semicircular line of Douglas)** ~ midway between umbilicus + pubis; (4) **Inguinal canal anatomy**: - Floor (posterior wall): transversalis fascia + conjoint tendon (medial) - Roof: internal oblique + transversus abdominis (conjoint) - Anterior: external oblique aponeurosis - Posterior: transversalis - Contents: spermatic cord (M) / round ligament (F) - **Hesselbach''s triangle**: medial — rectus, inferior — inguinal ligament, lateral — inferior epigastric vessels; (5) **Hernias — definitions**: - **Reducible**: contents return to abdomen - **Incarcerated**: stuck, irreducible, no ischemia - **Strangulated**: ischemic, surgical emergency - **Sliding**: part of sac is wall of viscus; (6) **Types of abdominal wall hernias**: a. **Inguinal**: - Indirect (lateral to inferior epigastric vessels — through deep ring, follows spermatic cord) — congenital patent processus vaginalis; common in pediatric + young adult - Direct (medial, through Hesselbach''s triangle) — acquired weakness; older - Femoral (below inguinal ligament, through femoral canal) — more in women; high incarceration risk → repair upon diagnosis b. **Umbilical** — congenital in children (usually closes by 5 yr); acquired in adults (pregnancy, obesity, ascites); repair if symptomatic or > 1-1.5 cm c. **Epigastric** — midline above umbilicus through linea alba defect; small fat-only often; repair if symptomatic d. **Spigelian** — at semilunar line below arcuate line; rare; high incarceration risk → repair e. **Lumbar** (Petit, Grynfeltt triangles) — rare; congenital or acquired f. **Incisional** — through prior surgical scar (10-20% of laparotomies); repair with mesh; component separation for large defects g. **Parastomal** — adjacent to stoma; common; complex repair h. **Perineal** — through pelvic floor; post-pelvic surgery or rare congenital i. **Internal hernias** (e.g., Petersen''s post-RYGB) — no abdominal wall defect, mesenteric defect inside; (7) **Surgical principles**: - Repair indication: symptomatic, complications, asymptomatic for incarceration-prone (femoral, Spigelian) - Mesh > primary suture in adults for lower recurrence - Pediatric: high ligation, NO mesh - Approach: open (Lichtenstein) vs laparoscopic (TEP, TAPP); robotic; - Component separation (anterior — Ramirez; posterior — TAR transversus abdominis release) for large complex ventral hernias - Mesh placement: onlay, sublay (preferred for ventral — retro-rectus), inlay (rare), preperitoneal/TEP (inguinal)"},{"label":"C","text":"All hernias same management"},{"label":"D","text":"No anatomy review needed"},{"label":"E","text":"Children always need mesh"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Abdominal wall anatomy + hernias** — surgical staple. Foundation: anatomic layers (skin → subQ → muscles + aponeuroses → transversalis fascia → peritoneum). Key structures: rectus sheath (varies above/below arcuate line), inguinal canal, linea alba, linea semilunaris, Hesselbach''s triangle. **Hernia types**: 1. **Inguinal** (most common): indirect (lateral to epigastric vessels), direct (medial, Hesselbach), femoral (below inguinal ligament — repair always, high incarceration) 2. **Umbilical** (children + adults) 3. **Epigastric** (midline above umbilicus) 4. **Spigelian** (semilunar line — high incarceration) 5. **Lumbar** (rare) 6. **Incisional** (10-20% post-laparotomy) 7. **Parastomal** (adjacent to stoma) 8. **Perineal** 9. **Internal hernias** (mesenteric defects, e.g., post-RYGB Petersen''s) **Surgical approaches**: - **Open Lichtenstein** (tension-free mesh) — gold standard inguinal - **Laparoscopic TEP** (totally extraperitoneal) or **TAPP** (transabdominal preperitoneal) — equal/better outcomes (chronic pain, bilateral repair, recurrent); lower learning curve - **Robotic** — increasing - **Component separation** (anterior Ramirez, posterior TAR) — for large complex ventral - **Mesh placement options**: onlay (top), sublay/retromuscular (preferred), inlay (rare), preperitoneal **Modern principles**: - Tension-free mesh for adult primary + incisional (lower recurrence) - Light-weight mesh — less chronic pain - Bioprosthetic (Strattice, biological) — contaminated field selectively - Avoid mesh in pediatric (growth) - Watchful waiting acceptable for asymptomatic minimally symptomatic inguinal in elderly (Fitzgibbons RCT) - Repair always for femoral, Spigelian (high incarceration) **Complications**: chronic pain (10-15%), recurrence (1-5%), seroma, infection, mesh complications (migration, erosion, infection, fistula). **Quality measures**: AHSQC (Americas Hernia Society Quality Collaborative), EHS standards.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'International HerniaSurge Guidelines 2018; SAGES Guidelines; Skandalakis Surgical Anatomy', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
