select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: ICU + nutritional support

คำถาม: critical care nutrition principles', '[{"label":"A","text":"No nutrition needed in ICU"},{"label":"B","text":"**Critical Care Nutrition (ASPEN/SCCM Guidelines)**: (1) **Initiation timing**: - **Early enteral nutrition (EN) within 24-48h** of ICU admission if hemodynamically stable + no contraindication - **Parenteral nutrition (PN)** only if EN contraindicated / insufficient ≥ 7 days (no benefit + harm with early PN — EPaNIC trial); (2) **Routes**: - **EN**: NG, NJ (post-pyloric — useful in gastroparesis, high aspiration risk, pancreatitis), gastrostomy, jejunostomy - **PN**: central (peripheral if short-term + low osmolarity); (3) **Caloric target**: - Early phase (acute, days 1-3): permissive underfeeding 50-70% (recent evidence — full feeds may worsen outcomes by overfeeding stressed metabolism) - Late phase: full feeds 25-30 kcal/kg/day; - Indirect calorimetry gold standard if available - Avoid hyperglycemia + overfeeding-associated complications (hepatic steatosis, hypertriglyceridemia, CO2 retention); (4) **Protein**: higher need in critical illness — 1.2-1.5 g/kg/day (up to 2 g/kg in burns, multi-trauma, CRRT) — preserve lean body mass; (5) **Composition**: - Carb: 40-60% of calories - Fat: 25-30% (including essential FA — linoleic, α-linolenic) - Standard polymeric formulas — most patients - Specialty: - High-protein - Concentrated (fluid restriction) - Fiber-containing - Renal-specific (low K, PO4, fluid) - Immunonutrition (arginine, omega-3 PUFA, RNA nucleotides — Impact, Oxepa) — selected (elective major GI cancer surgery shows benefit; mixed in critical care — controversial in sepsis); (6) **Electrolyte management**: monitor + adjust (Na, K, PO4, Mg) — refeeding syndrome prevention; (7) **Micronutrients + vitamins**: thiamine (especially before glucose load), vitamin D + others as deficient; selenium, zinc; antioxidants — RCT evidence mixed; (8) **Glycemic control**: target 140-180; avoid hyper + hypoglycemia (NICE-SUGAR — strict glycemic control 80-110 increased mortality); (9) **Gastric residual volumes (GRV)** — historically used to assess tolerance; recent evidence: NOT necessary for routine EN tolerance check (REGANE trial — outcomes not different with vs without GRV monitoring); promotility (metoclopramide, erythromycin short-term) if intolerance; (10) **Aspiration prevention**: head of bed 30-45°, postpyloric feeding if at risk, ETT cuff pressure adequate, monitor for high gastric residuals selectively; (11) **Constipation**: laxatives, prokinetics, bowel regimen; (12) **Refeeding syndrome**: severely malnourished — phosphate, K, Mg drops + thiamine deficiency → cardiac + neurological dysfunction; prevent: slow advancement + thiamine + electrolyte replacement; (13) **Special populations**: - Burns: hypermetabolic; high protein + calorie - Trauma: aggressive nutrition - Sepsis: early enteral, hypocaloric early phase - AKI/CRRT: protein loss higher with CRRT (1.5-2.5 g/kg) - Liver failure: balanced (don''t restrict protein) - Pancreatitis: early enteral (NJ tube past leak); reduces complications + mortality - Obesity: hypocaloric, high protein (1.5-2 g/kg ideal body weight); (14) **Discharge transition**: oral intake, oral supplements, home tube feeding, home TPN if needed; outpatient nutritional follow-up"},{"label":"C","text":"TPN for all"},{"label":"D","text":"NPO indefinitely"},{"label":"E","text":"Single formula for all patients"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Critical Care Nutrition (ASPEN/SCCM 2016 Guidelines + updates)** — important but historically under-prioritized. **Principles**: 1. **Early enteral nutrition (EN)** within 24-48h of ICU admission if stable + no contraindication — preserves gut barrier, reduces translocation, immune function, infection 2. **Parenteral nutrition (PN)** — only if EN insufficient/contraindicated ≥ 7 days; EPaNIC trial (NEJM 2011) showed early PN harmful (over-feeding, infection); 3. **Caloric target**: phase-dependent — early hypocaloric, advance later 4. **Protein target**: higher (1.2-1.5 g/kg, up to 2 g/kg in burns/CRRT) — preserve lean body mass during catabolic state 5. **Glycemic control**: 140-180 (NICE-SUGAR — strict harmful) 6. **Gastric residual volumes**: not routinely needed (REGANE) 7. **Aspiration prevention**: HOB 30-45°, postpyloric for high-risk **Specialty considerations**: - Pancreatitis: early enteral (PYTHON trial NEJM 2014; EarlyNJ studies) — reduces complications - Burns: hypermetabolic — high protein + calorie - Sepsis: early enteral, hypocaloric early - Obesity: hypocaloric + high protein per ideal body weight - Renal: protein NOT restricted in CRRT (high loss); restrict K, PO4 per renal function - Liver: don''t restrict protein; balanced **Refeeding syndrome**: in severely malnourished resuming nutrition → cells uptake K, Mg, PO4 + thiamine deficiency → cardiac arrhythmia, respiratory failure, neurologic; prevention: slow advance + thiamine pre-feed + monitor electrolytes + replace. **Immunonutrition** (arginine, ω-3 PUFA, nucleotides): - Elective major GI cancer surgery — benefit (Drover meta-analysis Ann Surg) - Critical illness/sepsis — controversial; some signal harm with arginine in septic shock; case-by-case **Glutamine** supplementation in ICU — REDOXS (NEJM 2013) showed harm with high-dose IV glutamine — discontinue routine use. **Selenium + antioxidants** — mixed evidence in critical care; not routine. **Indirect calorimetry** — gold standard for energy expenditure measurement when available + feasible; predictive equations (Harris-Benedict, Mifflin, ASPEN) widely used. **Discharge transition**: oral intake assessment, oral supplements, home tube feeding, home TPN if indicated; outpatient nutrition follow-up.', NULL,
  'medium', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'gi', 'adult',
  'ASPEN/SCCM Critical Care Nutrition Guidelines 2016; ESPEN ICU Guidelines; Casaer MP et al. NEJM 2011 (EPaNIC)', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
