select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: surgical microbiology — antimicrobial stewardship

คำถาม: antibiotic resistance + stewardship in surgery', '[{"label":"A","text":"Use broadest antibiotic always"},{"label":"B","text":"**Antimicrobial Stewardship — surgical perspective**: (1) **Why stewardship**: - Resistance increasing globally (WHO priority — top 10 health threats) - C. difficile infection (antibiotic exposure major risk) - Cost - Pharmacy + ID team integration; (2) **Stewardship principles**: a. **Right drug, right dose, right duration**: - Narrow spectrum when organism known - Broad-spectrum empirically when severe + then de-escalate per culture - Dose for site (some abscesses need high dose) + patient (renal, hepatic, weight) - Shortest effective duration b. **De-escalation** when culture + sensitivity available c. **Source control** — surgical, percutaneous drainage, removal of infected device d. **Pharmacokinetic / pharmacodynamic considerations**: - Time-dependent (β-lactams): time above MIC critical — extended infusion or continuous - Concentration-dependent (aminoglycoside, fluoroquinolone): peak/MIC ratio - AUC/MIC (vancomycin, linezolid); (3) **Common resistant organisms in surgical patients**: a. **MRSA** (Methicillin-Resistant Staph aureus): - SSI, IV catheter infections, pneumonia - Vancomycin, daptomycin, linezolid, ceftaroline, tedizolid - Decolonization protocols (mupirocin nasal + chlorhexidine bath) reduces SSI b. **VRE** (Vancomycin-Resistant Enterococcus): - Less virulent typically but limited options - Linezolid, daptomycin, tigecycline c. **ESBL-producers** (Extended-Spectrum β-Lactamase) — E. coli, Klebsiella: - Resist most cephalosporins + penicillins - Carbapenems (meropenem, ertapenem, imipenem), pip-tazo (selected), ceftolozane-tazobactam, ceftazidime-avibactam d. **CRE / CPE** (Carbapenem-Resistant Enterobacterales, Carbapenemase-Producing Enterobacterales): - Limited options: ceftazidime-avibactam, meropenem-vaborbactam, imipenem-relebactam, eravacycline, plazomicin, polymyxin (last resort, nephrotoxic) e. **Pseudomonas aeruginosa**: - Intrinsic resistance + acquired - Pip-tazo, cefepime, ceftazidime, meropenem, levofloxacin, aminoglycoside, ceftolozane-tazobactam f. **MDR Acinetobacter**: - Carbapenem-resistant common; very limited; colistin, tigecycline, sulbactam, eravacycline g. **Stenotrophomonas maltophilia**: - TMP-SMX first-line h. **Candida**: - Fluconazole (susceptible — albicans, parapsilosis often) - Echinocandin (caspofungin, micafungin, anidulafungin) — resistant Candida, severe - C. auris emerging multi-drug resistant; (4) **High-risk surgical populations**: prolonged hospitalization, prior antibiotic exposure, ICU, immunosuppressed, transplant, traveled from endemic regions; (5) **Stewardship implementation**: - Antimicrobial Stewardship Program (ASP) — required by Joint Commission + Medicare - Prospective audit + feedback - Formulary restriction + pre-authorization - Education - Surveillance + reporting - Order sets + clinical decision support - De-escalation protocols - IV-to-oral conversion - Allergy delabeling - C. difficile prevention bundles"},{"label":"C","text":"No oversight needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Same antibiotic for all infections"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid culture-directed therapy"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Antimicrobial stewardship** — central to modern infectious disease + surgical practice. WHO top 10 global health threats includes antimicrobial resistance. Drivers: overuse, misuse, broad-spectrum overreliance, agriculture, lack of new antibiotics. **5 Rs of antibiotic use**: 1. **Right diagnosis** — culture before antibiotic when feasible 2. **Right drug** — narrow when organism known 3. **Right dose** — patient-specific 4. **Right duration** — shortest effective (recent evidence supports shorter courses for many infections; e.g., 5-7 days for uncomplicated pneumonia, abdominal infection if source control adequate) 5. **Right route** — IV-to-oral conversion early when patient stable + absorption adequate **De-escalation** — switch from broad to narrow when sensitivity known. **Source control** — surgical/IR drainage, debridement, device removal — critical; antibiotic alone often inadequate. **Common resistant organisms (priority)**: 1. **ESKAPE** pathogens — common nosocomial multi-drug resistant: - Enterococcus (VRE) - Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) - Klebsiella pneumoniae (ESBL, CRE) - Acinetobacter baumannii (MDR/XDR) - Pseudomonas aeruginosa (MDR) - Enterobacter species 2. **Candida** including auris (emerging MDR) **New antibiotics**: - Ceftolozane-tazobactam (Pseudomonas, ESBL) - Ceftazidime-avibactam (CRE, KPC) - Meropenem-vaborbactam (CRE) - Imipenem-relebactam - Eravacycline (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Cefiderocol — siderophore cephalosporin (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Tedizolid (MRSA, VRE) - Delafloxacin **Stewardship program elements** (CDC core elements): leadership commitment, accountability, drug expertise, action (prospective audit + feedback, formulary), tracking, reporting, education. **MRSA decolonization** (CHG bathing + mupirocin nasal) — reduces SSI + MRSA infections in select surgical populations (cardiac, orthopedic). **Allergy delabeling** — important: > 90% of self-reported penicillin allergies are NOT true IgE allergies; delabeling enables use of effective + narrow first-line agents. **C. difficile prevention**: minimize broad-spectrum + duration; contact precautions; hand hygiene (soap > alcohol for C. diff spores); environmental cleaning.', NULL,
  'medium', 'id', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'id', 'adult',
  'IDSA Antimicrobial Stewardship Guidelines 2016; CDC Core Elements; WHO Global Action Plan AMR', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
