select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'EMS: surgical workforce + burnout

คำถาม: physician wellness + burnout in surgery', '[{"label":"A","text":"Burnout not relevant"},{"label":"B","text":"**Physician wellness + burnout in surgery — critical professional issue**: (1) **Definition** (Maslach Burnout Inventory): - Emotional exhaustion - Depersonalization (cynicism toward patients) - Reduced personal accomplishment; (2) **Prevalence**: - Surgeons 40-60% in US studies (varies by specialty + cohort) - General surgeons high; emergency, critical care, oncology elevated - Residents particularly vulnerable; (3) **Consequences**: - Personal: depression, anxiety, substance use, suicide (physicians higher rate than general population), divorce, decreased life satisfaction - Professional: medical errors (~ 2× increased), patient safety, decreased patient satisfaction, decreased empathy, turnover, early retirement, decreased career engagement - Healthcare system: increased costs, decreased quality, workforce shortage; (4) **Drivers**: - System: EHR burden, productivity demands, administrative tasks, regulatory burden, malpractice concerns, RVU pressure, work-hour intensity, on-call burden - Workplace culture: hierarchical, blame culture, lack of autonomy, inadequate teamwork - Individual: maladaptive coping, perfectionism, work-life imbalance, social isolation, financial stress; (5) **Prevention + intervention** — multilevel: a. **Individual strategies**: - Self-care: sleep, exercise, nutrition, hobbies, relationships - Mindfulness, meditation, CBT, professional therapy - Resilience training - Peer support, mentorship - Professional coaching - Setting limits, learning to say no; b. **Organizational/system**: - Reduce administrative burden (scribes, voice recognition) - Improve EHR usability - Wellness officers (Chief Wellness Officer increasing in academic centers) - Schedule design (limit on-call burden, flexible scheduling) - Peer support programs - Mental health services (low barrier, confidentiality protected) - Just culture (vs blame) - Leadership training - Compensation models that don''t solely reward volume; c. **Professional/cultural**: - Destigmatize seeking help - Mental health resources for clinicians (e.g., RISE — Resilience in Stressful Events at Hopkins; Anesthesia Patient Safety Foundation; ACS Surgeon Wellbeing) - Peer support after adverse events (second victim phenomenon) - Bereavement support after patient death - Professional society initiatives; (6) **Surgeon-specific challenges**: - Long training (5-10+ years) - Sleep deprivation - Adverse outcomes psychological impact - Lawsuit risk - Demanding patient care + family demands - Identity tied to work; (7) **Special populations**: - Trainees (high burnout, hidden curriculum exposure) - Women + minority physicians (often face additional stressors — discrimination, harassment, work-family balance) - Mid-career - Late career; (8) **Wellness as patient safety + quality issue** — increasingly recognized; not just individual responsibility; (9) **Mental health crisis among physicians**: - Suicide rate physicians higher than general population (especially female physicians ~ 2× rate) - License restrictions for mental health treatment historically (modernizing — many states now ask only about current impairment vs ever diagnosis - help-seeking should be supported) - Substance use - Depression - Anxiety; (10) **Building wellness culture**: leadership, accountability, measurement (annual surveys), evidence-based interventions, allocate resources, integrate into strategic planning"},{"label":"C","text":"Stigmatize seeking help"},{"label":"D","text":"Single intervention"},{"label":"E","text":"Individual responsibility only"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Physician burnout + wellness** — major contemporary issue in medicine + surgery; recognized as quality + safety issue, not just individual challenge. **Burnout definition** (Maslach): emotional exhaustion + depersonalization + reduced personal accomplishment. **Prevalence in surgery**: 40-60% — highest in general surgery, EM, critical care, oncology; residents particularly vulnerable. **Consequences**: - Personal: depression, anxiety, substance use, divorce, suicide (physicians 2-4× general population, especially female physicians) - Patient: medical errors 2× increased, decreased satisfaction, decreased empathy - Healthcare: turnover, early retirement, costs, workforce shortage **System drivers** (largest factors): - EHR burden + administrative tasks - Productivity demands - Regulatory + malpractice burden - On-call + sleep disruption - Workflow inefficiencies - Inadequate staffing - Culture (hierarchical, blame) **Multilevel intervention**: 1. **Individual**: self-care, mindfulness, CBT, peer support, professional help-seeking, boundary-setting 2. **Organizational/system**: - Reduce EHR + admin burden - Schedule + workload optimization - Wellness officers + programs - Mental health services (confidential, low-barrier) - Peer support programs - Just culture - Leadership training - Recognition + appreciation 3. **Professional/societal**: destigmatize, mental health licensure reform, peer support, professional society initiatives (ACS, AMA, surgical specialty societies) **Second victim phenomenon**: clinicians distressed by patient adverse events — need debriefing, peer support, mental health resources (RISE program Hopkins, etc.). **Mental health licensure**: historically asked about ever diagnosis or treatment → barrier to seeking help; modernizing — questions should focus on current impairment, not history of treatment (American Medical Association advocates; FSMB updated guidance). **Trainee burnout**: very high rates; ACGME duty hour limits, wellness curricula, mental health resources, harassment + mistreatment policies (hidden curriculum exposure significant issue). **Quadruple aim** — original Triple Aim (better care, better health, lower cost) expanded to add clinician wellbeing as essential. **Quality + safety connection**: physician wellbeing correlates with patient outcomes; burnout associated with increased errors, lower patient satisfaction, decreased empathy + adherence to evidence — wellness is patient safety issue. **Special populations** — women, minority, LGBTQ+ physicians often face additional stressors (discrimination, harassment, work-family expectations).', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'ems_mgmt', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'ACS Surgeon Wellbeing Resources; National Academy of Medicine Action Collaborative on Clinician Wellbeing; Maslach C et al.', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
