select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Integrative: gender-affirming care + surgery

คำถาม: gender-affirming surgical care principles', '[{"label":"A","text":"Reject all gender-affirming care"},{"label":"B","text":"**Gender-affirming surgical care — multidisciplinary patient-centered**: (1) **Terminology**: - **Gender identity** vs sex assigned at birth - **Cisgender** (identity matches assigned sex) vs **transgender** (does not) - **Non-binary** — outside binary - **Gender dysphoria** — distress from incongruence (DSM-5 diagnostic criterion historically required for some insurance/surgical access — moving away from pathologization); (2) **Care framework**: - **WPATH (World Professional Association for Transgender Health) Standards of Care 8 (2022)** — global guidance - **Endocrine Society Guidelines** for hormone therapy - Multidisciplinary: mental health, endocrinology, plastic/urologic/gynecologic surgery, primary care, voice + speech therapy, fertility specialist; (3) **Components of care** (not all individuals desire all): - **Social transition** — name, pronouns, presentation - **Mental health support** - **Hormone therapy**: - Feminizing: estradiol + anti-androgen (spironolactone, GnRH agonist) - Masculinizing: testosterone - Monitoring + complications - **Pubertal suppression** in adolescents (GnRH agonist) — reversible; allows time for decision-making - **Surgery** — multiple options; (4) **Gender-affirming surgeries**: a. **Top surgery**: - Masculinizing: bilateral mastectomy + chest contouring - Feminizing: breast augmentation b. **Bottom surgery**: - Masculinizing: hysterectomy + BSO, vaginectomy, scrotoplasty, phalloplasty (radial forearm free flap, ALT, others) or metoidioplasty (clitoral release + extension), testicular prosthesis - Feminizing: orchiectomy, penectomy, vaginoplasty (penile inversion most common, peritoneal or intestinal alternatives), labiaplasty, clitoroplasty, vulvoplasty c. **Facial feminization / masculinization** (FFS / FMS): forehead, jaw, brow, rhinoplasty, tracheal shave/augmentation, chin contouring d. **Voice surgery** — feminizing (cricothyroid approximation, Wendler glottoplasty) — adjunct to voice therapy; (5) **Pre-surgical requirements** (WPATH 8 — modernized, less restrictive than prior): - Persistent + well-documented gender dysphoria - Capacity to consent - Age of majority (or pediatric protocols with multidisciplinary team for adolescents) - Significant medical/mental health conditions reasonably well controlled - 12 months of continuous hormone therapy as appropriate (for some procedures) — though increasingly individualized; (6) **Post-op care**: - Surgery-specific protocols - Long-term care: dilation regimens (vaginoplasty), continued hormone therapy, follow-up - Mental health support - Continued cancer screening based on anatomy (Pap if cervix remains, prostate if prostate remains, breast if breast tissue remains); (7) **Reproductive considerations**: - Fertility preservation counseling before hormone therapy or surgery - Options: sperm cryopreservation, oocyte/embryo cryopreservation, ovarian/testicular tissue (selected); (8) **Insurance + access**: - Coverage variable - Advocacy + legal protections (Affordable Care Act US protects against discrimination — currently contested) - International variation significant - Equity concerns - Health disparities; (9) **Adolescent care** — particular complexity: - Pubertal suppression — reversible - Hormone therapy — partially reversible - Surgery — generally deferred until adulthood, with exceptions (chest surgery sometimes considered earlier with multidisciplinary input + family); (10) **Outcomes**: high satisfaction; reduces mental health distress + suicide risk in many studies; ethics + politics ongoing; cultural competency essential"},{"label":"C","text":"Surgery without evaluation"},{"label":"D","text":"Discrimination acceptable"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid multidisciplinary care"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Gender-affirming surgical care** — increasingly recognized component of comprehensive medical care for transgender + gender diverse individuals. **WPATH Standards of Care 8 (2022)** — globally recognized framework; updated less restrictive criteria + recognizes diversity of gender identity + expression; multidisciplinary care model; individualized approach. **Comprehensive care components**: 1. **Social transition** — supported by mental health 2. **Hormone therapy**: - **Feminizing**: estradiol (oral, transdermal, injection) + anti-androgen (spironolactone or GnRH agonist; bicalutamide; finasteride for some) - **Masculinizing**: testosterone (injection, gel, patch) - Monitoring: hormone levels, hematocrit (testosterone), lipid + LFT, BP, mood, cardiovascular risk - Long-term: cancer risks, cardiovascular, fertility 3. **Pubertal suppression** in adolescents (GnRH agonist — leuprolide, others) — reversible; allows time + reduces distress 4. **Surgery** — various procedures; not all individuals desire all **Surgical procedures**: - **Top surgery**: masculinizing (chest masculinization with mastectomy + reconstruction) or feminizing (augmentation) - **Bottom surgery**: - **Vaginoplasty** — penile inversion (most common), peritoneal pull-through, intestinal (sigmoid colon — usually for prior failed PIV, complex; risk of mucus, malignancy long-term) - **Phalloplasty** — radial forearm free flap (gold standard, sensate), anterolateral thigh (ALT), latissimus, fibula osteocutaneous - **Metoidioplasty** — clitoral release + extension (testosterone-hypertrophied clitoris), urethroplasty, vaginectomy - Hysterectomy ± BSO - Orchiectomy - Penectomy, scrotoplasty - **Facial feminization / masculinization**: multiple procedures - **Voice surgery**: cricothyroid approximation, Wendler glottoplasty - **Hair**: electrolysis (genital area pre-vaginoplasty), scalp transplant for masculinizing **Pre-surgical evaluation**: persistent gender dysphoria, capacity, age of majority (or adolescent protocols), medical/mental health stability, hormone therapy if appropriate. WPATH 8 removed previous requirement of separate mental health letters for many procedures + emphasizes individualized assessment by qualified provider. **Post-op care**: - Vaginoplasty: dilation regimen (initially several times daily, tapering — lifelong some dilation needed), wound care - Phalloplasty: stages (urethroplasty, glansplasty, erectile/testicular prosthesis), complications (urethral stricture, fistula common) - Continued hormone therapy + monitoring - Mental health support - Continued cancer screening based on remaining anatomy: Pap if cervix, breast if tissue, prostate if prostate **Fertility preservation**: counseling before hormone therapy or surgery; gamete cryopreservation, ovarian/testicular tissue (experimental). **Outcomes**: high satisfaction in majority; substantial mental health benefit in studies (reduces depression, anxiety, suicidality); regret rates low (< 1-2%) in modern series with appropriate evaluation. **Advocacy + access**: insurance coverage variable + contested; legal protections vary; substantial health disparities; cultural competency essential for providers.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'WPATH Standards of Care 8 (2022); Endocrine Society Transgender Guidelines 2017; ACS Statement on Care of Transgender Patients', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_integrative'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'Integrative: gender-affirming care + surgery

คำถาม: gender-affirming surgical care principles'
  );

