select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 30 ปี post-laparoscopic Roux-en-Y gastric bypass 6 ชั่วโมงก่อน — มา ED ด้วยอาการ tachycardia + abdominal pain + agitation; vital signs: HR 138, BP 88/52, Temp 38.4, lactate 5.4

คำถาม: differential + management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Observation in PACU"},{"label":"B","text":"**Early post-bariatric tachycardia + hypotension + lactate elevation — multiple potentially catastrophic etiologies**: (1) **Anastomotic leak** (most concerning early): gastrojejunostomy or jejunojejunostomy leak — peritonitis, sepsis, multi-organ dysfunction; - Diagnosis: CT with oral contrast (rapid + sensitive — extravasation, free air, fluid), upper GI contrast study; - High index of suspicion — tachycardia + new abdominal symptoms + lactate / fever after bariatric = leak until proven otherwise - ''Tachycardia is the most sensitive sign of leak'' — HR > 120 should trigger workup - Treatment: emergent re-exploration (laparoscopic or open) + drainage + repair + drain + NPO + TPN + antibiotic; (2) **Bleeding** (intra-abdominal or GI luminal): - Stapler line bleeding most common - Mesenteric, omental, spleen capsule, trocar site - Diagnosis: drop in Hb, CT, endoscopy if luminal - Treatment: stable → observe + transfuse; unstable → re-explore + control; (3) **Pulmonary embolism** — high risk in bariatric (obesity + immobility + surgery + hypercoagulable); CTPA; treatment: anticoagulation; massive PE → thrombolytics, embolectomy; (4) **Bowel obstruction** — early often from anastomotic stenosis or technical issue (less common in immediate post-op vs late internal hernia); (5) **Other**: cardiac (MI), sepsis non-surgical (UTI, pneumonia, line), aspiration, rhabdomyolysis (long surgery, positioning); (6) **Initial response**: ABC, resuscitation + IV fluid + IV antibiotic broad-spectrum + type & cross + STAT CT abdomen + surgical consult + transfer to ICU; (7) **Re-exploration threshold low**: in bariatric, post-op deterioration warrants liberal re-exploration — delay = mortality; (8) **Multidisciplinary**: bariatric surgery, anesthesia, ICU, IR, cardiology as needed"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"D","text":"Aspirin alone"},{"label":"E","text":"Continue feeding"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Early post-bariatric deterioration** — life-threatening differential. **Key principle**: tachycardia after bariatric surgery = leak until proven otherwise. **Sentinel signs of anastomotic leak**: - Tachycardia (most sensitive — HR > 120) - Hypotension - Abdominal pain (variable in laparoscopic post-op patient — incision pain confounds) - Fever - Tachypnea - Anxiety / agitation - Decreased UO - Lactate elevation **Diagnosis of leak**: 1. CT with oral + IV contrast — most sensitive; can detect extravasation, free fluid, free air 2. Upper GI contrast (Gastrografin) — alternative 3. Diagnostic laparoscopy — gold standard when high suspicion + imaging negative **Management of leak**: 1. Resuscitation (fluid, vasopressor, antibiotic broad-spectrum) 2. Re-exploration: identify leak, repair primarily if early + healthy, drain, omental coverage, JJ tube for feeding 3. ICU monitoring 4. TPN initially → enteral via JJ tube → oral as healing 5. Drain management 6. Antifungal if persistent / mycotic 7. Endoscopic stent for contained / late leak — selected **Other early complications**: - Bleeding (staple line, mesenteric, trocar, spleen) - PE (high risk in obese + bariatric) - Mechanical bowel obstruction (rare immediate, common late internal hernia) - Cardiac, pulmonary, infectious **Late complications**: - Marginal ulcer (gastrojejunal anastomosis) - Internal hernia (Petersen''s, JJ, transverse mesocolon) - Anastomotic stenosis - Nutritional deficiency - Weight regain - Dumping syndrome - Cholelithiasis - Hypoglycemia (post-bariatric reactive) - Bone density loss **Prevention** of leak: meticulous technique, proper staple line testing (leak test intraop), drain placement (selective), perioperative VTE prophylaxis. **VTE prophylaxis** essential — bariatric high-risk: mechanical + chemical (enoxaparin or LDUH); some centers use extended prophylaxis 7-10 days postop; consider for obese, prior VTE, immobility. **Patient education**: signs to return — fever, tachycardia, severe pain, vomiting, dysphagia, melena.', NULL,
  'hard', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'gi', 'adult',
  'ASMBS Position Statement on Anastomotic Leak; MBSAQIP Standards; Aurora AR et al. Obes Surg', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
