select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Clinical: gynecology — ovarian mass

คำถาม: ovarian mass workup + management', '[{"label":"A","text":"All masses are benign"},{"label":"B","text":"**Ovarian mass — workup + management**: (1) **Initial assessment**: - History (menstrual, hormonal, pain, GI/GU symptoms, family history) - Exam (size, mobility, tenderness, ascites) - Imaging: transvaginal + transabdominal US first-line (size, complexity, septa, solid components, papillary, vascularity); MRI for indeterminate; CT for staging if malignancy suspected - Tumor markers based on age + features: - **CA-125** — epithelial ovarian Ca surveillance + post-menopausal mass; many false positives (endometriosis, menstruation, pregnancy, peritoneal inflammation) - **AFP, β-hCG, LDH** — germ cell tumor (especially young women) - **CEA** — mucinous (could indicate GI primary metastatic) - **Inhibin, AMH** — sex cord-stromal - **HE4** — adjunct to CA-125 (ROMA, RMI algorithms) - **ROMA, RMI, OVA-1** — risk algorithms; (2) **Premenopausal**: - Most common functional cysts (follicular, corpus luteum) — typically resolve - Endometriomas - Mature cystic teratoma (dermoid) - Mucinous + serous cystadenoma - Germ cell tumors (rare but ~ 5% of ovarian cancer in young) - Borderline + epithelial cancer less common than postmenopausal; (3) **Postmenopausal**: - Most concerning age for malignancy - Any solid component, complex features → higher malignancy risk - Refer to gynecologic oncologist for staging + appropriate surgery; (4) **Acute complications**: - **Ovarian torsion** — surgical emergency: severe pain, US Doppler flow assessment (may be normal — clinical suspicion important); detorsion + ovarian preservation when feasible (oophorectomy if non-viable); + oophoropexy if predisposing factors - **Hemorrhagic cyst rupture** — usually self-limited; observe if stable; surgery if hemodynamically unstable; (5) **Surgical approach**: - Laparoscopic preferred for benign-appearing masses (cystectomy preserving ovary in reproductive-age, oophorectomy in postmenopausal) - Open surgery for large, malignant, complex - In suspected malignancy → gynecologic oncologist + comprehensive staging laparotomy (peritoneal washings, omentectomy, lymph node dissection, biopsies); (6) **Ovarian cancer**: - Epithelial (most common — high-grade serous most common subtype, often with TP53; BRCA association) - Germ cell (young women — dysgerminoma, yolk sac, etc.) - Sex cord-stromal (granulosa cell, Sertoli-Leydig) - Borderline (low malignant potential) - Metastatic (Krukenberg from gastric, breast, colon) **Stage I-IV**; debulking surgery (cytoreduction to no visible disease — R0 cytoreduction strongest prognostic factor) + platinum-based chemo (carboplatin + paclitaxel); maintenance bevacizumab; PARP inhibitor maintenance (BRCA+, HRD+, all newly diagnosed advanced — PRIMA, PAOLA-1); (7) **Genetic counseling** indicated — BRCA1/2 (10-15% ovarian Ca), Lynch (10%), other; cascade testing; (8) **Prevention**: - Oral contraceptive use reduces ovarian Ca risk (50% if 5+ yr) - Tubal ligation - Risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy in BRCA+ + others (age 35-45) - Opportunistic salpingectomy at other gyne surgery emerging (recognize STIC — serous tubal intraepithelial carcinoma — fallopian tube origin of high-grade serous ovarian Ca per modern understanding); (9) **Patient-centered**: fertility preservation if reproductive age + benign or selected malignant (germ cell, borderline)"},{"label":"C","text":"Surgery for all masses"},{"label":"D","text":"No workup needed"},{"label":"E","text":"Same approach all ages"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Ovarian mass** — common; differential by age + features. **US characterization (IOTA criteria)** + tumor markers + clinical features guide management. **Algorithm**: 1. **TVUS** — primary imaging 2. **Markers** age-appropriate: - CA-125 — post-menopausal especially - AFP, β-hCG, LDH — young women (germ cell) - HE4, ROMA, RMI — risk algorithms 3. **MRI** — indeterminate cases 4. **CT** — staging if malignancy 5. **Surgical evaluation** — by appropriate surgeon (gynecologist for benign-appearing, gynecologic oncologist for suspected malignancy) **Common ovarian masses by age**: - **Reproductive (15-45)**: functional cysts (follicular, corpus luteum), endometrioma, mature cystic teratoma (dermoid), cystadenoma (serous, mucinous), borderline tumor, germ cell, less commonly epithelial cancer - **Postmenopausal (> 45-50)**: any complex mass concerning for cancer; benign also possible (cystadenoma, fibroma) **Ovarian cancer types**: 1. **Epithelial** (90%): - High-grade serous (most common; often BRCA, TP53; thought to arise from fallopian tube — STIC lesion) - Low-grade serous - Endometrioid - Clear cell - Mucinous (often borderline; if invasive consider GI primary) - Brenner 2. **Germ cell** — young women (teens-30s); dysgerminoma, immature teratoma, yolk sac, choriocarcinoma, mixed; treatable + curable even advanced 3. **Sex cord-stromal** — granulosa cell (estrogen-producing), Sertoli-Leydig (androgen-producing), thecoma, fibroma 4. **Metastatic (Krukenberg)** — from gastric, breast, colon **Surgical management**: - **Benign-appearing premenopausal**: laparoscopic cystectomy (preserve ovary if reproductive-age + benign-appearing) - **Benign-appearing postmenopausal**: laparoscopic oophorectomy ± salpingectomy - **Suspected malignancy**: gynecologic oncologist; staging laparotomy (peritoneal washings + omentectomy + lymph node sampling + biopsies); cytoreductive surgery for advanced (R0 strongest prognostic factor) - **Adnexal torsion**: surgical emergency; detorsion + preservation when feasible; oophoropexy if recurrent **Ovarian cancer treatment**: - Surgery (debulking — R0 cytoreduction = no visible disease — best outcomes) - Adjuvant chemo (carboplatin + paclitaxel) - Maintenance bevacizumab (advanced) - PARP inhibitor maintenance (olaparib, niraparib, rucaparib) — BRCA+, HRD+, or all newly diagnosed advanced (PRIMA, PAOLA-1, SOLO-1 trials) - Recurrence: platinum-sensitive (> 6 mo) vs resistant **Genetics**: BRCA1/2 (10-15% ovarian Ca), Lynch (10%), other genes (PALB2, RAD51 family, ATM); cascade testing of family; risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy. **Risk reduction**: oral contraceptives (50% reduction if 5+ yr), tubal ligation, RR salpingo-oophorectomy in BRCA+ at 35-40 (BRCA1) / 40-45 (BRCA2), opportunistic salpingectomy (emerging — STIC theory — fallopian tube origin of high-grade serous).', NULL,
  'medium', 'obgyn', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'obgyn', 'adult',
  'ACOG Practice Bulletin Adnexal Mass; NCCN Ovarian Cancer; ESMO; SGO Statements', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
